We are a premium manufacturer of laminate flooring planks of virtually any style, shape, finish, texture, scrape, bevel, locking system, thickness, size and attached pad. We started operations in the US in 2000 and opened our manufacturing facility in South Carolina in 2005. Our parent company, the Swiss Krono Group, is based in Switzerland.

Since our launch, our amazing growth and our ability to supply the needs of the marketplace have earned us the nickname "The Quiet Giant" of laminate flooring that is proudly made by and for Americans.
Yes. Laminate flooring can be installed over above-grade $floor

An above-grade concrete floor will most likely be in a commercial building. If that’s the case and you’re not the building owner, you’d better check first. If the building is new construction, the concrete must be completely cured for a minimum of 90 days before installation. We would still recommend a 6-mil vapor barrier and, of course, underlayment padding before installing laminate flooring.
Yes. Laminate flooring can be installed over below-grad $floor

But be careful on the below-grade. These are usually found in residential basements, and you must be careful about moisture migration from the ground through the concrete. We recommend several ways to test this and steps you can take to control it. And, the concrete must be completely cured a minimum of 90 days. You must use a 6-mil vapor barrier and, of course, underlayment padding. Drains of any kind, French or otherwise, are clear indicators that this concrete floor is not acceptable for laminate installation.
For laminate flooring, plank thickness is measured in millimeters (mm). A millimeter is roughly 0.039 inches.

Flooring products like Swiss Krono USA’s Designer Floor Planks will state plank thickness on their packages or in their advertising by measuring the entire plank thickness — from the bottom surface that rests on the subfloor to the top of the plank.

Everything has to go. Only the subfloor may remain when you install laminate.
Carpet, its padding, and all its staples must be completely removed — down to the subfloor — before you install laminate flooring.
Some types and styles of commercial or “indoor/outdoor” carpeting may look harmless, but it and any adhesive used to glue it down must be removed before installing a laminate floor.

Not necessarily; a thicker laminate could be manufactured with lower-quality materials. Swiss Krono USA uses a superior high-density fiber (HDF) core made of 50% southern yellow pine and 50% hardwood in our laminate floors, no matter what the thickness is. Every component of our laminate floor is important in every product we make.

There advantages to a thicker plank laminate floor. A thicker plank is easier to install. It’s actually a bit forgiving because it can better span minor subfloor deviations without problems later. “Levelness” is important to a successful installation. Since a laminate floor is a floating floor, a subfloor that has a peak or valley of over 1/8th of an inch within 40 inches of grade is not good.
Plus, a thicker plank can provide superior acoustics. Because the plank is thicker, sound doesn’t travel as well. And a thicker plank provides better impact resistance.

There are four standard laminate-flooring plank thicknesses on the market. As you might expect, the thinner the plank the less expensive the laminate floor. Our Designer Floor Planks come in the three thickest measurements: 8 millimeter (8 mm), 10 millimeter (10 mm) and 12 millimeter (12 mm).
